{"items":[{"title":"Color is a mathematical nightmare","link":"https://www.theverge.com/tech/643638/color-models-spaces-gamut-mathematical-nightmare","pubDate":"2025-04-06T11:00:00.000Z","author":"Jess Weatherbed","content":"\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\n<figure>\n\n<img alt=\"\" data-caption=\"Breaking down the confusing world of color spaces.\" data-portal-copyright=\"\" data-has-syndication-rights=\"1\" src=\"https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/03/257572_Spec_Week_CVirginia_B_COLOR.jpg?quality=90&#038;strip=all&#038;crop=0,0,100,100\" />\n\t<figcaption>Breaking down the confusing world of color spaces.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\">The best method that we have for defining color is by using math. Specifically, <a href=\"http://www2.mat.dtu.dk/people/J.Gravesen/pub/48-2015-colour.pdf\">mind-boggling mathematical models</a> called color spaces that use geometry to assign colors as a fixed point that we can reference, ensuring the blue<em> </em>that I see is the same blue <em>you</em> see. As a creative-leaning person who can barely split a bill without a calculator app, all that math is extremely daunting.</p>\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\">The good news is that computing software will do all these complicated calculations for us, allowing us to rely on our eyeballs to pick whatever colors look best. The bad news is that there&acirc;&#128;&#153;s an equally daunting number of color spaces to choose from, and they&acirc;&#128;&#153;re all optimized for different tasks across web design, photography, video editing, physical printing, and more. And if you select the wrong one at any point between creating, editing, and viewing something, it can really mess with what colors are supposed to look like.</p>\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-none\">It&acirc;&#128;&#153;s a lot to absorb. Thankfully, most of us will only ever need to understand the basics, and that knowledge can be useful to everyone &acirc;&